The feeling of the god's replies is well kept in Horace’s lines, but there is much freedom in the reproduetion, especially in the substitution sor the ‘lock of hair' and the ⁴ thyrsus ’ of the luxuries which the Roman man of wealth values, the closing of the dialogue with the answer of Dionysus, that he can have his release at will, and the turn which Horace gives to this answer (see note on v. 78). Horace has stopped the dialogue at the place that suits him, and the interpretation which he puts on the words is also arbitrary, and one which could hardly suit the actual speeches. Dionysus’ freedom is recovered in the play by his exercise of divine power.
